, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Godmanchester, Huntingdonshire, England":"Godmanchester, Huntingdonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England"},"en":{"1586–December 1660":"1586–December 1660","1586–1654":"1586–1654","1612–1708":"1612–1708","1586–1660":"1586–1660","11 Jun 1611":"11 June 1611","December 1660":"December 1660","September 1654":"September 1654","1660":"1660","1612":"1612","1600":"1600","1654":"1654","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1586":"1586","1651":"1651","1708":"1708","Godmanchester, Huntingdon, England":"Godmanchester, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","Godmanchester, Huntingdonshire, England":"Godmanchester, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hudson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Hudde</i> (see   Hudd  ) + <i>-son</i>. This surname is also established in Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Hodsdon","meanings":["English (Buckinghamshire and Middlesex): habitational name from Hoddesdon (Hertfordshire), from an Old English personal name <i>Hodd</i> (genitive <i>Hoddes</i>) + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’. The surname was probably confused with   Hudson  .","History: The earliest known bearer of this name is Norman de Hoddesdon, recorded in 1165–66. The surname was taken to America by Nicholas Hodsdon <i>c.</i> 1628, from whom probably all current US bearers of the name are descended."]},{"name":"Hodson","meanings":["English:","variant of   Hudson  .","patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Hod(e)</i>, a variant of <i>Ode</i>, + <i>-son</i>. See   Ott   and   Oates  ."]},{"name":"Hudd","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Hudde</i> (Anglo-Norman French <i>Hud(de)</i>), a pet form of <i>Hue</i>; see   Hugh  ."]},{"name":"Hutson","meanings":["English:","variant of   Hudson  .","variant of <b>Hotston</b>, perhaps a habitational name from a lost place in Harting (Sussex), from an Old English personal name <i>Hod</i> (genitive <i>Hoddes</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. It may survive in the name <i>Hudsons Copse</i> in that parish, in which case it could be a source of the surnames <i>Hotson</i>, <i>Hodson</i>, <i>Hudson</i>, and <i>Hutson</i> in Sussex."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705208,"age":1,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":14,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":34,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705213,"age":56,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"John Hudson was born in 1586, in Huntingdonshire, England. He married Alice Cade on 11 June 1611, in Godmanchester, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in December 1660, in Godmanchester, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1586–December 1660":"1586–detsember 1660","1586–1654":"1586–1654","1612–1708":"1612–1708","1586–1660":"1586–1660","11 Jun 1611":"11. juuni 1611","December 1660":"detsember 1660","September 1654":"september 1654","1660":"1660","1612":"1612","1600":"1600","1654":"1654","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1586":"1586","1651":"1651","1708":"1708","Godmanchester, Huntingdon, England":"Godmanchester, Huntingdonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Godmanchester, Huntingdonshire, England":"Godmanchester, Huntingdonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England"},"fi":{"1586–December 1660":"1586–joulukuu 1660","1586–1654":"1586–1654","1612–1708":"1612–1708","1586–1660":"1586–1660","11 Jun 1611":"11. kesäkuuta 1611","De